This needs GLSLOptimizerSharp to be added to the dependencies repo before it can build.
I haven't added the new stuff for Mac yet in the Protobuild definitions. I did add Linux and tested both the Windows and Linux build on Windows. I have only tested a single shader at this point, the translated version of SpriteEffect:

```
uniform mat4 MatrixTransform;
uniform sampler2D Texture;


attribute vec4 position: POSITION0;
attribute vec4 color    : COLOR0;
attribute vec2 texCoord : TEXCOORD0;

varying vec4 vColor;
varying vec2 vTexCoord;

void SpriteVertexShader()
{
    gl_Position = MatrixTransform * position;
    vColor = color;
    vTexCoord = texCoord;
}

void SpritePixelShader()
{
    gl_FragColor = texture2D(Texture, vTexCoord) * vColor;
}

technique SpriteBatch 
{
    pass 
    {
#if GLES
        VertexShader = compile glsl_100 SpriteVertexShader();
        PixelShader  = compile glsl_100 SpritePixelShader();
#else
        VertexShader = compile glsl_110 SpriteVertexShader();
        PixelShader  = compile glsl_110 SpritePixelShader();
#endif
    }
};
```
The build system can only handle old GLSL (attribute, varying), some more effort will be needed to support in/out/inout.

Discussion in #2167.
Sorry for all the whitespace changes :/

Ping @tomspilman

So I've seen some games use `SpriteBatch` for particles at times (or particle like things).  While this works it is inefficient because generally the code looks like this:
```
foreach (var e in myemitters)
{
    spriteBatch.Begin();
    foreach (var p in e.particles)
       spriteBatch.Draw(e.Texture, p.Position, e.SourceRect, p.Color, p.Rotation, GetOrigin(p), p.Scale, p.FlipEffects, p.Depth);
    spriteBatch.End();
}
```
This is arguably the most expensive version of `Draw` and many redundant calculations occur for each draw.

For sure #5347 will help.

Also you could argue that people shouldn't do this... write your own rendering using a vb/drawprim that is customized to your particle system design.

But it made me think we could add some additional methods to `SpriteBatch` that help reduce redundancy when lots of related draws are made.  First and foremost when the texture/srcRect is shared which is common when you are drawing many instances of the same thing which happens a lot in games.

One approach would be to add a default texture and source rect to begin:
```
SpriteBatch.Begin(Texture2D, Rectangle, SpriteSortMode, BlendState, SamplerState, DepthStencilState, RasterizerState, Effect, Matrix);
```
Maybe a this begin call should have some alternate name.

Then add additional draw methods that don't require any texture info and instead use the pre-calculated defaults.

While @nkast has done some great work with his low level optimizations there is still more to be done.

For example all of these functions in `SpriteBatch`:
```
void Draw(Texture2D texture, Vector2 position, Color color);
void Draw(Texture2D texture, Rectangle destinationRectangle, Color color);
void Draw (Texture2D texture, Vector2 position, Rectangle? sourceRectangle, Color color);
void Draw (Texture2D texture, Rectangle destinationRectangle, Rectangle? sourceRectangle, Color color);
```

All redirect to the same `DrawInternal` method which does a common set of optimizations.  We do this mainly to make the code easier to read and maintain as well as to void bugs.  This however comes at the expensive of performance.

Take `void Draw(Texture2D texture, Vector2 position, Color color)` for example.  This draw doesn't need rotation, doesn't need flipping of sprites, doesn't need UV calculations.  If this function created its own `SpriteBatchItem` internally it could do so much more efficiently than `DrawInternal` does now.

Same goes for the other specializations of `Draw` and `DrawFont` in `SpriteBatch`.  This matters when games are drawing 1000s for sprites per frame.

While this does mean a lot more duplicate code... it also means much more performance.  We can deal with the issue of duplicate code via more unit tests.  Performance here is more important.

Using:
- NuGet WindowsDX package 3.6.0.1184 OR Dev installer from downloads page
- Visual Studio 2015
- Windows 10 Home Insider Preview

Steps to recreate:
- Create new project
- Add Monogame WindowsDX package 3.6.0.1184
- Add this to Initialize:
```
    protected override void Initialize()
    {
      // TODO: Add your initialization logic here
      graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1920;
      graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 1080;
      graphics.ToggleFullScreen();
      base.Initialize();
    }
```
- Set a breakpoint anywhere in the Update method
- Run project

Problem:
Game launches, breakpoint is hit, but game window gets stuck in the foreground and it's very hard to close it.  Alt tab, windows key, even ctrl+alt+escape for task manager doesn't work.  The only way I've gotten around it is by using the multiple desktop function of Insider Preview to open task manager on another desktop and then killing vshost32.exe.  I've done some experimentation and it seems like it's not actually crashed, it just doesn't yield foreground control to Visual Studio.  I can drag VS to another desktop and it functions normally, properly stopped at the breakpoint I set.

This fixes the parse error that would occur when you have a sampler as a parameter in a function described in #5315. Does not yet fix the bug when declaring a sampler as a local parameter.

When a sampler is declared and not immediately assigned inside a function, the parser will not crash but the sampler will be incorrectly registered as a sampler of the shader. When a sampler is declared and assigned in one statement inside a function the parser will crash. I didn't find a good way to solve this yet :/ 

@tomspilman Am I using a different version of TinyPG or something? Asking because of all the missing comments. I got the latest from the SickheadGames branch.

@Danthekilla Can you test your shaders with this branch? Preferably all those that you ported to make sure nothing's broken. You can get the build artifacts from the teamcity page when it's done building. I'll post a link when it's done.

Dragging the vertical separator in the Pipeline Tool of the left side of the window will cause a crash due to `Drawable.Width` not accepting negative values. Easy fix is to use 0 if the value is negative, but maybe it makes more sense to have a minimum width (larger than 0). 
If you drag the seperator all the way to the right it can go beyond the visible window, making it impossible to make the build view visible again without resizing the window. 
@cra0zy

long story short, i made a game that creates a sprite on the location of my mouse left click event but it is offcentered by half the window size.  I have to multiply the mouse state x,y by 2 in order for it to work.

How it should be:
if (Mouse.GetState().LeftButton == ButtonState.Pressed) {
Mine mine = new Mine(mineSprite, Mouse.GetState().X, Mouse.GetState().Y);
}

Temporary bug fix: 
if (Mouse.GetState().LeftButton == ButtonState.Pressed) {
Mine mine = new Mine(mineSprite, Mouse.GetState().X*2, Mouse.GetState().Y*2);
}
